Does "Hello.java" in RMI creates stub, skeleton, helper, holder, operations file  like "Hello.idl"   in CORBA/

Short answer: No, Hello.java in RMI does NOT generate stub, skeleton, helper, holder, or operations files like Hello.idl does in CORBA.

🧠 Why the Difference?
🔹 In CORBA (using IDL like Hello.idl)
You define interfaces in IDL (language-independent)
The IDL compiler generates multiple files:
Stub
Skeleton
Helper
Holder
Operations

👉 Because CORBA is designed to work across different programming languages

🔹 In Java RMI (Hello.java)
You define everything directly in Java (no separate IDL)
Java handles most things automatically
⚙️ What RMI Generates
✅ Stub
Yes (historically)
Generated using rmic tool
Acts as a proxy on the client side
❌ Skeleton
No (modern Java)
Older Java versions (pre-Java 5) used skeletons
Now handled internally by JVM via reflection
❌ Helper / Holder / Operations
No
Not needed because:
RMI is Java-to-Java only
Uses built-in serialization and interfaces
📌 Modern RMI (Important)
You usually don’t run rmic anymore
Stubs are generated dynamically at runtime
So even stub files may not physically exist
🆚 Quick Comparison
Feature	RMI (Hello.java)	CORBA (Hello.idl)
Interface format	Java	IDL
Stub	Yes (auto/dynamic)	Yes (generated)
Skeleton	No (obsolete)	Yes
Helper	No	Yes
Holder	No	Yes
Operations	No	Yes
Language support	Java only	Multi-language
✅ Final Answer

Hello.java in RMI does not create stub, skeleton, helper, holder, or operations files like CORBA’s Hello.idl.
RMI relies on Java interfaces and built-in mechanisms, and most of the plumbing is handled automatically.


